The order of the three setAttribute calls definitely doesn't matter since all they do is set a bit in a bit field [1] which is commutative.                                I have read the bug that lead to the introduction of this comment [1] and here's the important bit:                                <quote>                This is needed in an SCM system for example if a file is marked as executable then it should be brought over and the execute bit set not just for owner but according to the umask. It is exactly the role of per-process umask to determine who gets permission when it is only known generically (i.e. this file is executable).                </quote>                                In other works some implementations could decide that when you set a file owner-executable they'll consult the umask to maybe set the file group-executable and other-executable as well.  So when you set some bits you might end up with more bits set than expected but never less.  I couldn't find an implementation that does this however.                                In our case it doesn't really matter because we force all three executable bits to 1 so they will always end up all set.  In reality we only care that the user/owner has the permission to execute the file so we could also skip setting it for group/others...                                [1] https://bugs.eclipse.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=259643

I don't think WeakHashMap will work for this use case.                                The documentation of WeakHashMap says that it keeps weak references to the keys and strong references to the values.                                In this case the keys are Long objects storing PDOM record numbers and the values are IValue objects.                                Since the map keeps weak references to keys in order for a mapping to remain in the map code elsewhere needs to keep a strong reference to the Long object used as the key. However that won't happen - no one keeps a strong reference to the Long object created in PDOMLinkage.loadValue().                                Even if we were to say store the Long object in PDOMCPPVariable to keep it alive different PDOMCPPVariable instances will store different Long objects (since Long does not guarantee that every instance representing the same value is the same object) and only one of them (the first one to add the mapping to the cache I guess) would keep the value alive defeating the purpose of the cache.                                I think what would work instead is a class that's similar to WeakHashMap but that stores weak references to the values and strong references to the keys. That way the value is kept alive as long as at least one PDOMCPPVariable refers to it.

Yes I think this will work thanks!                                A couple of questions:                                  1) Should we periodically iterate over the map and                     remove mappings where the value has become null?                                  2) Is there any reason to prefer making the key and                     value types Object and Object instead of Long                     and IValue? Perhaps the idea is that later this                     cache can be re-used for other purposes besides                     storing values? (In that case could we name it                     something more general like fWeakResultCache?)
Yes I think clearResultCache is a good place. Thanks!

wrong synchronization (double-check locking problem). the class is currently used from a single method so synchronization is not necessary. if you are concerned about some future uses just add javadoc comment that the class is not thread-safe.

'final' parameters has no effect on Map members so it does not matter.                                For double-checked locking in general you can read more detailed explanation in http://www.cs.umd.edu/~pugh/java/memoryModel/DoubleCheckedLocking.html but in short HashMap does not use 'volatile' for its members and can't be safely used with double-checked locking                                I think this is a good example of premature optimization:                * this code does not currently need synchronization at all                * there is no evidence that straightforward/conservative does not yield adequate performance                                I suggest we remove synchronization and deal with it when/if we have to.                                 Reworking the code to eagerly populate parameters map in constructor is another viable alternative in which case it will be possible to use ImmutableMap and simplify the code otherwise.
